Germany, year zero
The 8th of May always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was really a decisive moment in my life
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our small street, in the outskirts of western Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide as I did after my liberation from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
The Nazis having left, the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We pillaged the shops in the neighborhood. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry retrieved from a bookstore.
I was 16 years old. The occupying armies were committing all sorts of excesses.
It was difficult to obtain food.
My father was taken directly from his prison to the center of Berlin, and tasked with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply department.
For a certain period of time, there was neither electricity, nor transportation, nor organized life.
Defeat or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate question, even though for our family it was obviously a liberation in all senses of the term.
Mais pour quoi faire ?
Pour quel avenir ?
“ Tu dois aider ”, me dit ma mère.
Je proposai donc mes services aux autorités soviétiques locales et participai à la livraison de produits alimentaires de base à quelques points de distribution de notre district de Zehlendorf.
Cinq semaines plus tard, j’étais de retour à l’école.
I had a special card for being a “victim of fascism”, while others wore an Iron Cross obtained for late services rendered to the army.
Certainly, some were refugees from the East, many had seen their house destroyed by bombings, almost all were crying for the disappearance of close relatives.
Yet, this stage did not last.
It is almost unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the “economic miracle” in Germany.
Or more precisely, the economic miracle in West Germany.
The differences between occupation powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and mainly accompanied by new enslavement.
Camps like Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and detainees.
On the other hand, after a brief period of non-fraternization, the Western powers adopted a policy of controlled autonomy reinforcement.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was not an empty word, and it was based on German traditions.
Of course, not everything was benevolence on the part of the occupying powers.
It was also the beginning of the Cold War, and each one wanted to consolidate "their" part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first one is of an economic order, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy is anchored incontestably more easily in a context of economic relaunch.
To achieve this, one must above all have initiative, from individuals who are eager to put an end to a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (like those of Ludwig Erhard, father of the “social market economy” in Germany), but things are easier with initial capital.
Which is why American support through the Marshall Plan is important.
The European Union has also helped the formerly communist countries and continues to accompany them in their approach.
The other lesson, of a moral order, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of the Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany did not undertake its long path by worrying about the past.
In fact, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of “restoration”, because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in their posts.
In a certain way, the country ignored its past to move forward towards the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany faced up to its past, with a lot of success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other wounded countries therefore lead to confusion.
Yet, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to assume the past.
In the end, it's a better method.
En Europe, the 8th of May 2005 is an occasion to look at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and therefore filled with hope.
